    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="brand-context">
    <div class="brand-context-inner">
      <div class="section-number">01</div>
      <div class="brand-context-content">
        <h2>How to Diagnose an LG Linear Compressor Failure</h2>
        <p>The LG linear compressor failure has a distinctive signature that experienced technicians recognize immediately. The most reliable indicator is a rhythmic clicking or click-buzz pattern from the rear of the refrigerator — typically every 2-3 seconds. This is the compressor attempting to start, failing, and resetting via the overload. Error code 67 (compressor lock) will appear in the diagnostic mode.</p>
        <p>Before condemning the compressor, a proper diagnosis checks the start relay first. Removing the relay and shaking it — if it rattles, the relay has failed internally. A bad relay produces identical symptoms to a failed compressor and costs $25 to fix instead of $400+. We see this misdiagnosis regularly in the field: homeowners told they need a compressor who actually needed a relay.</p>
        <p>If the relay is solid and compressor winding resistance tests correctly (3-7 ohms across terminals, no ground fault), the internal linear mechanism has failed. At that point, warranty coverage is the critical question. For models and years covered by the settlement, LG provides the replacement compressor at no cost and reimburses labor. We handle the warranty claim process on your behalf.</p>

        <h2>LG Washer OE Error — Almost Never a Pump Failure</h2>
        <p>The OE drain error is the most common LG washer call we receive. Homeowners frequently assume it's a pump failure — it almost never is. LG front-load washers have a drain pump filter behind a small access panel at the lower right front of the machine. This filter catches lint, coins, hair ties, and other debris from every wash cycle. LG recommends cleaning it monthly. Most people don't know it exists.</p>
        <p>When the filter clogs completely, the pump can't move water past it and the OE code triggers. The fix: open the access panel, drain the water, unscrew the filter, clean it, reinstall. No parts. We do this on site in 20-30 minutes and show the homeowner the filter location and cleaning procedure. If the filter is clear and the pump itself is seized or failed, that's a parts repair — but that's the exception, not the rule.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

